					&lt;p&gt;OK, I am giving two answers to this after I thought about it. If you &lt;em&gt;REALLY&lt;/em&gt; want to stay super traditional to the spirit of the day and dig deep into your English roots, you would have some a nice &lt;a href="https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~pwp/tofi/medieval_english_ale.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"&gt;medieval beer&lt;/a&gt;, or nice &lt;a href="http://www.greydragon.org/library/13thCenturyMead.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"&gt;Mead&lt;/a&gt; and/or some type of &lt;a href="http://www.archiveofciderpomology.co.uk/origins_of_cider.htm" rel="nofollow noreferrer"&gt;cider&lt;/a&gt;. Unless you were royalty, you wouldn't have access to wine from France.&lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;p&gt;All of the above would be a great match for Goose.&lt;/p&gt;

